{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fdd1dd10-edfd-47ae-8cb6-a8f5c53a6326","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is exactly what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but doesn't upgrade anything. If your workloads are simply *outdated* (not corrupted), this won't help.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after that, you can also try a clean restore:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet nuget locals all --clear\ndotnet restore\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"95b62985-faf7-41fc-b47e-cbf39cca578a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search any codebase for this.","outputTokens":265,"requestId":"3C28:8F118:D558F7:1091869:6A0128FA"},"id":"4725cc25-c551-4c20-af32-a10b2f4accbe","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:55:31.343Z","parentId":"f05791b4-0ae6-4eab-9e9c-23feec85ddae"}
